<section id="what-inaction-costs" class="reveal">
  <h2>The Precise Cost of Doing Nothing</h2>
  <p>The framing of pharmacogenomics as a horizon technology — something medicine is moving toward, a future to be anticipated — has served a useful institutional function. It has allowed the system to position inaction as patience rather than negligence. The future framing has been in circulation for approximately twenty years. In that time, CPIC has published 28 guidelines. The FDA has labeled 541 drugs. The PREPARE trial has run, reported, and been replicated in sub-cohorts. The RIGHT 10K study has found actionable variants in 99% of subjects. The Dutch model has put a number — 419 — on the annual death toll from just four gene-drug pairs in a country of 17.9 million people.</p>
  <p>The bottleneck is not the science. CPIC surveys confirm this explicitly: the field has moved past proof-of-concept. The barriers are education, reimbursement, and institutional will. These are not technical problems. They are political and economic ones, and they have political and economic beneficiaries. A system that does not test for CYP2D6 status before prescribing antidepressants generates more prescriptions, more follow-up appointments, more hospitalizations, and more medications to manage the side effects of the first medications. The inefficiency is not neutral. It is profitable for some actors and catastrophic for patients.</p>
  <p>Return to the three genes. CYP2C19, CYP2D6, SLCO1B1. Three genes. Seventy-five percent of genetically preventable drug harm in 1.3 million reports. A panel test covering all three costs less than a single emergency department visit. The Dutch model found 419 preventable deaths per year from four gene-drug pairs in a population of 17.9 million. Scale that to the United States — 335 million people, 15% of all prescriptions carrying pharmacogenetic influence, a healthcare system that processes hundreds of millions of drug initiations annually — and do the arithmetic yourself. The number is not small.</p>
  <p>The central irony of pharmacogenomics is not that the science is hard. The science is mature. The irony is that we built a system capable of matching molecules to bodies with extraordinary precision, published the guidelines, labeled the drugs, ran the trials, counted the deaths — and then decided the bodies weren't worth the paperwork.</p>
</section>

